# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biodiversity-heritage-library
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The **Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University**, formerly the **Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia**, is the oldest natural science research institution and museum in the Americas.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] It was founded in 1812, by many of the leading naturalists of the young American republic with an expressed mission of "the encouragement and cultivation of the sciences".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] It has sponsored expeditions, conducted original environmental and systematics research, and amassed natural history collections containing more than 17 million specimens.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy also organizes public exhibits and educational programs for both schools and the general public.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] During the first decades of the United States, Philadelphia was the cultural capital and one of the country's commercial centers.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Two of the city's institutions, the Library Company and the American Philosophical Society, were centers of enlightened thought and scientific inquiry.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The increasing sophistication of the earth and life sciences, combined with a growing awareness of the variety of life and landscape in the American wilderness, led a small group of naturalists to establish the Academy of Natural Sciences in the winter of 1812.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The academy was meant to foster a gathering of fellow naturalists and to nurture the growth and credibility of American science.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] They frequently looked to their European counterparts for inspiration and expertise and longed to be regarded as equals.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] On 25 April 1817 they were incorporated into the society under the title of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia by the legislature of Pennsylvania.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] By 1 January 1818, eight members were published.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 2011, the Academy became affiliated with nearby Drexel University and changed its name to the Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Within a decade of its founding, the Academy became the undisputed center of natural sciences in the United States.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Academy members were frequently enlisted to participate in national surveys of the western territories and other major expeditions.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Thomas Jefferson of Virginia, John Edwards Holbrook of South Carolina, Thomas Nuttall and Richard Owen of the United Kingdom, Georges Cuvier of France, and Alexander von Humboldt of Prussia were among the corresponding members (members who lived far from Philadelphia) of the Academy's first decades.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Later during the 19th century, other notable naturalists and scientists, including John James Audubon, Charles S.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Boyer, John Cassin, Edward Drinker Cope, Ezra Townsend Cresson, Richard Harlan, Ferdinand V.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Jefferis, John Lawrence LeConte, Joseph Leidy, Samuel George Morton, George Ord, and James Rehn were members.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Corresponding members included Charles Darwin along with his supporters Asa Gray, and Thomas Henry Huxley.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] For much of its history, new members had to be nominated by two current members and then elected by the remaining members.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] These requirements were dropped in 1924.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Notable 20th-century scientists include James Böhlke, James Bond, Henry Weed Fowler, Ruth Patrick, Henry Pilsbry, H.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy of Natural Sciences holds an internationally important natural history collection.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Currently, there are over 18 million biological specimens, and hundreds of thousands of volumes, journals, illustrations, photographs, and archival items in its library.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] These collections were obtained through multiple means, including the donation or purchase of existing collections or individual items, the collection activities of Academy-sponsored expeditions, or those of individual scientists, whether or not they work at the Academy.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Some collections were originally gathered by other institutions.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] For example, a number of the natural history collections at the American Philosophical Society were relocated to the Academy by the end of the 19th century.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Traditionally, researchers at natural science (or natural history) institutions such as the Academy engaged in biological taxonomy, the science of discovering, describing, naming, and classifying species.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In recent decades, research has shifted in emphasis to the science of systematics, the study of the evolutionary relationships among these species.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy preserves many type specimens, the reference material that helps establish a species' identity.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] They also preserve additional specimens with which scientists can investigate the nature of these species, their relationships with other species, their evolutionary history, or their conservation status.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's collections include a wide range of specimens across the tree of life.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The museum also maintains several historically important collections.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Botany is study of plants, including nonvascular bryophytes (mosses, liverworts, and hornworts) and vascular plants, including ferns, conifers and flowering plants.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The field of botany has also traditionally included the study of algae, lichens, and fungi which are now classified in different biological kingdoms.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Collections at the Academy, which are housed in the Philadelphia Herbarium (PH), the oldest institutional herbarium in the New World, include some of the oldest and most important botanical collections in the Americas.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Notable early collectors include Benjamin Smith Barton, Constatine Rafinesque, Thomas Meehan, Thomas Nuttall, and Fredrick Pursh.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The herbarium contains approximately 1.5 million specimens of vascular plants, fungi, lichens, algae, and fossil plants, 40,000 of which are types.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] It also contains some special collections, including the plants collected by Johann and Georg Forster during the voyages of Captain James Cook, and by Meriwether Lewis during the Lewis and Clark expedition (Corps of Discovery).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The department's current focus is plant biodiversity and evolution focusing on Apocynaceae (milkweed or dogbane family) and Polygalaceae.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's Diatom Herbarium, the largest in the Americas and the second largest in the world, contains approximately 220,000 slides of these microscopic algae.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The herbarium contains many specimens contributed by notable collectors, a diversity of fossil diatoms, and diatoms collected as part of numerous freshwater environmental surveys in the United States.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Diatom Herbarium also provides collections and taxonomic services for the Phycology Section of the Patrick Center for Environmental Research.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Former curators of note include Charles S.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Boyer, Ruth Patrick, and Charles Reimer.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Entomology has been important to the Academy since its founding.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Two of its earliest members include Thomas Say, regarded as the father of American entomology, and Titian Peale, a leading natural history illustrator and the chief naturalist on the United States Exploring Expedition (1834–1842).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The entomology collection currently contains more than 3.5 million specimens and includes the Titian Peale Moth and Butterfly Collection, the oldest entomology collection in the United States.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator Emeritus, Daniel Otte, an expert on Orthoptera (crickets, grasshoppers, and their relatives) is a pioneer of presenting biological data on the internet through the creation of the Orthoptera Species File.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator and Entomology Department Chair, Jon Gelhaus is a leading expert on crane flies and manages the Mongolian Aquatic Insect Survey.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Ichthyology has also been a part of Academy collections and research since its beginnings, but the size of the collection was relatively modest until acquisition of Edward Drinker Cope's personal collections in 1898.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] A few years later, Henry Weed Fowler began his tenure at the Academy, during which he systematized the collections and described 1,408 species.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Böhlke, William Saul, and William Smith-Vaniz are among the scientists who followed Fowler.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator Emeritus, John Lundberg, an expert in catfishes, pioneered deep channel collecting in large tropical rivers and is the lead author of a seminal scientific paper on the biological and geographic history of the Amazon River Basin.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Ichthyology collection, which currently houses nearly 1.2 million specimens and nearly 3,000 types, is one of the most important such collections in the United States.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The department also hosts the All Catfish Species Inventory (a comprehensive online resource on catfish) and Catfish Bones (an online digital atlas of catfish morphology), and is a participant in Neodat II (an online resource of Neotropic ichthyology collections).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Two of the early members of the Academy, Thomas Say and Isaac Lea, were malacologists (see also conchologists).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Tucker Abbott, Samuel Stehman Haldeman, Henry A.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Tryon, Jr. were other noted malacologists who worked at the Academy.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's malacology collection is the oldest such collection in the United States and is the 3rd largest in the world.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] It currently contains over 10 million specimens, including types erected by more than 400 authors.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator Gary Rosenberg, an expert on Jamaican land snails, is a leader in digitised museum collections and research data.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Research websites include the Malacology Georeferencing Project an online database of Western Atlantic Marine Mollusca (Malacolog) Archived September 24, 2015, at the Wayback Machine, and the OBIS Indo-Pacific Mollusc database.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Research associate and former curator Danielle Graf, an expert on Unionidae (freshwater mussels), maintains the MUSSEL Project web site.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The majority of ornithologists active in the United States during the first half of the 19th century, including Charles Lucien Bonaparte, George Ord, Titian Ramsay Peale, John James Audubon, John Cassin, Thomas Nuttall, and John Kirk Townsend, were active members of the Academy.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Later notable Academy ornithologists include James Bond, Frank Gill, Rodolphe Meyer de Schauensee, Pete Myers, Fred Sheldon, and Witmer Stone.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] With nearly 200,000 specimens representing over 9,000 species, the Ornithology collection is one of the largest and most taxonomically complete bird collections in the world.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Delaware Valley Ornithological Club (DVOC) has held regular meetings at the Academy since 1890.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Vertebrate paleontology in the United States originated in Philadelphia through the efforts of naturalists and scientists associated with the American Philosophical Society (APS) during the first decade of the 19th century and at The Academy of Natural Sciences thereafter.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] By the end of the 19th century, the holdings from the APS, including the Thomas Jefferson Fossil Collection, had been transferred to the Academy for safekeeping.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Currently, the collection contains more than 22,000 specimens, including many types.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Richard Harlan was an early member who introduced many American naturalists to the groundbreaking works of Georges Cuvier.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Joseph Leidy, who described *Hadrosaurus* and alerted the scientific world to the paleontological treasures of the American West, is considered the "father" of American vertebrate paleontology.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Edward Drinker Cope, who also worked extensively on other vertebrates, is best known for his rivalry with Othniel Charles Marsh during the infamous Bone Wars.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Daeschler is currently studying the evolution of Devonian tetrapods, but he will be retiring in September 2023.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] He is a co-discoverer of the transitional "fishapod" *Tiktaalik roseae* from the Canadian Arctic and the discoverer of two tetrapods, *Hynerpeton* and *Densignathus* from the Catskill Formation in Pennsylvania.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy houses several collections of smaller size yet historical and scientific importance.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The general invertebrate collection contains about 22,600 specimens, while the invertebrate paleontology collection contains about 105,000 lots.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Generally, 21,500 specimens are gaunt, 13,500 are affiliated skins, and 1,700 are wet-preserved specimens.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Myers Rotifer Collection is the most comprehensive collection of rotifers on microslides.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The herpetology collection contains about 40,000 specimens, including more than 500 type specimens.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The mammalogy collection contains about 36,000 specimens and 180 holotypes.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Among the naturalists and scientists associated with these collections are Timothy Conrad, Edward Drinker Cope, Richard Harlan, John Edwards Holbrook, William W.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Jefferis, Henry Charles Lea, Isaac Lea, Joseph Leidy, Samuel George Morton, and Thomas Say.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Formerly the Limnology Department, the Patrick Center for Environmental Research focuses on applied ecology.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Founded in 1947 by Ruth Patrick, formerly of the Diatom Herbarium, it was one of the earliest U.S. environmental consulting concerns.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Its attachment to the Academy led it to become the first to employ interdisciplinary teams of scientists to study freshwater systems and the first to regard biodiversity as a central criterion of water quality.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Its 1948 biological survey of the Conestoga River Basin in Pennsylvania, a milestone in environmental research, led to similar surveys and studies throughout much of the United States.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Characteristically, these earlier projects were joint projects of the Limnology Department and private industry.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Since the rise of the environmental movement in the 1960s and 1970s and the resulting increases in governmental regulation of water pollution, the environmental assessments pioneered at the Academy are increasingly conducted by private environmental consulting firms.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Some of the work employs most of the center's expertise and capabilities, such as recent studies on the ecological effects of small dams or the ecological benefits of riparian reforestation.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Other studies may involve only one or a couple of the research programs.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] For example, a current project sampling sediment cores in tidal marshes throughout the Delaware Estuary.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] This undertaking, possibly the most comprehensive core sampling in any estuary, relies extensively on the center's expertise in biogeochemistry and phycology.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Once the sampling is completed, scientist will be able to investigate historical trends in marsh development, carbon, nitrogen and phosphorus cycling, water pollution, salinity variations, and climatic change by analysing the core's sediments, chemistry, and diatom assemblages.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Biogeochemistry Section of the Patrick Center is concerned with the influence of aquatic organisms on the sources, fate and transport of chemicals in aquatic systems.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Studies frequently deal with the carbon and nutrient cycling as well as those of trace elements (e.g., lead, copper, mercury, and zinc) and organic contaminants such as polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs), and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The section regularly provides water, sediment and tissue analyses for government, intergovernmental agencies, and private companies from around the country.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition to the sediment core project mentioned above, it has recently studied the effects of small dams on sediment contaminants, photochemical transformation of marsh-derived dissolved organic matter, and sedimentation and eutrophication in salt marshes.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Ecological Modeling Section employs sophisticated and rigorous mathematical modelling techniques to address a variety of questions in basic and applied research.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Examples include watershed-scale modeling and risk assessment; nonlinear population models structured by age, body size, or space; particle transport in turbulent aquatic systems; and the ecology and control of exotic invasive plants in urban parks.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Fisheries Section of the Patrick Center conducts research into the ecology, conservation, and management of lotic and estuarine fishes.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Studies may range from the analysis of fish tissues for contaminants, monitoring fish populations for environmental assessments, to investigating the life histories of individual species.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Benthic macroinvertebrates (primarily aquatic insects, crustaceans, and mollusks) are useful for biological monitoring programs.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Their varied life spans, ranging from weeks to years, are long enough to reveal intermittent and continuous pollutants, yet short enough respond to worsening or improving water quality.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Macroinvertebrate Section at the Patrick Center has extensive experience in bioassessment, biomonitoring, and inventorying of freshwater habitats throughout the United States.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Because of their great diversity and specific ecological requirements, algae, particularly diatoms, make excellent indicators of water quality.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Moreover, diatoms are readily preserved in sediments, which make them useful organisms for studying paleolimnology (the long-term trends of streams and lakes).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Phycology Section of the Patrick Center provides algal analyses for governmental and other agencies interested in both assessing water quality and long-term environmental trends.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] One such undertaking is the analyses of diatom assemblages in lake sediments (sediment cores) throughout the eastern United States.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] This work, part of a large project managed by the EPA, will try to establish reference (pre-anthropogenic) conditions for lakes throughout the country.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition to these research efforts, the Phycology Section of the Patrick Center has developed a set of online resources Archived September 6, 2019, at the Wayback Machine for using algae in environmental research.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] These include an algal image database, autecology datasets for freshwater algae, algae research with the USGS National Water-Quality Assessment (NAWQA) program, and a diatom paleolimnology database.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] For most of its history, biological taxonomy and systematics were conducted using comparative morphology.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In recent decades, however, advances in molecular biology and computational technologies have opened new possibilities for studying the diversity and history of life through the use of cladistics and computational phylogenetics.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] These technologies also offer new opportunities for molecular ecology and conservation genetics.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Academy scientists have been early adapters of molecular biology techniques.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Allozymes, DNA-DNA hybridization, immunoelectrophoresis, restriction site analyses of mitochondrial DNA and serology were used extensively since the late 1960s.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Recent molecular work mainly employs DNA sequencing, microsatellites, and AFLP (amplified fragment length polymorphism).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 2004, the Laboratory for Molecular Systematics and Ecology (LMSE) was formed as a shared, multi-user facility to improve access to and provide training for the use of molecular data in systematic and ecological research.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition to supporting staff, the lab offers research opportunities for students and post-doctoral fellowships.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's work in Mongolia started with the realization of the unique research opportunities available at Lake Hovsgol (Hovsgol Nuur).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] This large lake and its watershed were remarkably pristine and relatively unknown, especially in comparison to its sister lake in Russia, Lake Baikal.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1995, a multidisciplinary team of scientists from the Academy, as well as from other American institutions, Mongolia, Russia, and Japan started a multi-year study of the lake's biodiversity, limnology, and watershed.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Although this research was scientifically rewarding, it was apparent that issues concerning environmental protection and sustainable economic development needed addressing.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Consequently, work at Hovsgol shifted to ecosystem studies and capacity building.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] One early undertaking was the enhancement of the operational and physical infrastructure at Hovsgol National Park.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Long-term ecological monitoring of several tributary watersheds began in 1997 and soon the site would be adopted into the International Long Term Ecological Research Network.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Recent work at Hovsgol is focusing on the consequences of and sustainable responses to climate change.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The region lies in a transitional zone between the semi-arid Eurasian Steppe (grasslands) to the south and the Eurasian Taiga (boreal forest) to the north.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] As such, it is an ideal mid-continental site at which to monitor the ecological effects of climate change.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, changes in livestock herding practices raise concerns about overgrazing and desertification.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In response, the team at Hovsgol created and distributed a *Herder Handbook* and continues to conduct research and work with nomadic herders to develop sustainable practices.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Mongolian Aquatic Insect Survey is a multi-year biodiversity survey, environmental monitoring and capacity building project managed by Jon Gelhaus of the Academy's Entomology Department.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] A total of 217 sites from the Selenge River Basin, the most populous and most extensive drainage in Mongolia, were surveyed from 2003 to 2006.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Most of these sites are in rivers or streams, but some are in freshwater and saltwater lakes, hot and cold springs, and marsh wetlands.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Additional sites from the remote drainage systems in western Mongolia will be sampled in 2008.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The survey has yielded numerous new species and hundreds of geographic records for known aquatic insects, provided an extensive dataset for ongoing environmental monitoring, and has helped develop research and technical infrastructures in Mongolia.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] This capacity building includes, in collaboration with the Institute of Meteorology and Hydrology, the building of the first research laboratory in Mongolia dedicated to the study of aquatic invertebrates.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] It also includes training of Mongolian scientists and students.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Center for Environmental Policy informs and engages various constituents, promotes solutions, and builds public and professional awareness on important environmental topics.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Much of its activities focus on public programs and working groups.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The center hosts or participates in a number of public programs that are free and open to the public.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Urban Sustainability Forums feature panels of local and national experts discussing environmental and sustainability topics as they relate to the Philadelphia region.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Town Square, which may feature a panel or an individual, addresses a variety of topics relating to the environment or public science.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The center also hosts candidate forums, conferences and workshops.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The center acts as a logistical hub for a number of Working Groups organized around sustainability issues.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Currently active groups include one for condominium and building co-op owners, a network of faith-based environmental groups, and a forum of senior executives in the private sector.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Library and Archives were established at the Academy's founding meeting in 1812 for the purpose of supporting its natural science research.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The library provides online access, services, collections, imaging, and shared resources with other libraries.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The library houses nearly 200,000 volumes ranging from works published in the 16th century to current journals and books.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Its holdings also include illustrated works from as early as the 15th century, including Konrad Gessner's *Historia animalium*, Maria Sibylla Merian's *Insects of Surinam*, Edward Lear's *Psittacidae or Parrots*, and a double elephant folio of John James Audubon's *The Birds of America*.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Journal of the Academy of Natural Sciences* was the first peer-reviewed publication in the United States devoted to the natural sciences.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] By 1842, it had been superseded by the *Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences*.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Proceedings* have been published continuously since 1841.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Journal* was reborn in 1847 as a larger-format publication that could accommodate longer articles and monographs.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy publishes three other series.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The occasional series *Notulae Naturae* began in 1939 as a means to quickly publish short items, usually not longer than 16 pages on subject areas such as zoology, botany, ecology, geology and paleontology.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Monographs* series, which began in 1935, is composed principally of larger systematic reviews of selected taxonomic groups.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Special Publications* series, begun in 1922, includes works such as biography, taxonomy, historical reviews, and collections surveys.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] VIREO (VIsual REsource for Ornithology) is the most comprehensive collection of bird images in the world.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Started in 1979, the collection contains over 180,000 photographs representing over 7,300 species.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The collection contains work by some of the world's most talented photographers.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] VIREO licenses bird images for a wide variety of commercial and non-profit uses.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy first opened its collections to the public in 1828.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The popularity of its exhibits soared in 1868 with the debut of the world's first mounted dinosaur skeleton, *Hadrosaurus*.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The size of the crowds flocking to this display prompted the Academy to relocate to its present-and roomier-location in 1876.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] As with most museums in the 19th century, there was little separation of the Academy's collections, which were vital to scientific work, and the public spaces.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Not only did this subject the collections to extra wear and tear, but visitors were typically confronted with a bewildering assemblage of specimens with little in the way of supplemental information.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Over time, however, museums such as the Academy started to showcase their more popular specimens while sequestering the bulk of the collections.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, they spent more effort interpreting their public displays.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Museums started to play a more active role in educating the public.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] One expression of this transformation was the rise of that icon of natural history museums, the diorama.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] These three-dimensional displays were the virtual reality of their time, providing generations of museum visitors with their only opportunity to experience distant places and exotic wildlife.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Green created The Academy's first diorama, depicting rocky mountain goats.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Green's work was at first controversial amongst The Academy's staff, due to both the cost and accusations of sensationalism, but proved popular amongst the public.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1935, the Works Progress Administration began providing artists to help work on the dioramas, fueling the exhibits' continued expansion.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] By presenting the wilderness to the public, dioramas nurtured an appreciation of our natural heritage, which, coincided with the growth of the Conservation Movement in the United States.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy currently has 37 dioramas, most of which were installed in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] They feature a variety of animals from Africa, Asia, and North America.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Some of these, such as the caribou, lion, and plains zebra are familiar and relatively common, but others, such as the desert bighorn, kiang, Kodiak bear, panda, and passenger pigeon, are threatened, endangered, or extinct.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 2018, under the management of Drexel University, The Academy renovated some of the older dioramas.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] These renovations were meant to increase the scientific accuracy of the displays and improve their aesthetics.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Another icon of natural history museums is the dinosaur skeleton.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The first of these, the *Hadrosaurus* mount created by noted natural history artist Benjamin Waterhouse Hawkins, made its debut at the Academy in 1868.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] *Hadrosaurus* mounts also found their way into other public venues, including Princeton University, the Royal Scottish Museum, the Smithsonian, and the 1876 American Centennial Exposition.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] A special exhibit on the history of *Hadrosaurus foulkii* ran from November 22, 2008 to April 19, 2009.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] A skeletal mount of a related dinosaur, *Corythosaurus*, served as the centerpiece of the Academy's "Hall of Earth History" during the middle of the 20th century.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1986, the Academy opened a new exhibit, "Discovering Dinosaurs".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] This was the first large-scale exhibit to incorporate the findings of the "dinosaur renaissance".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Instead of cold-blooded and lumbering reptiles, dinosaurs were conceived as active-and possibly warm-blooded-animals more akin to birds than reptiles.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1979, another type of dinosaur was the subject of an exhibition at the academy when it featured Jim Gary's Twentieth Century Dinosaurs and found that it was an enormous success with the public.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1979, the academy also opened "Outside-In", a hands-on children's nature museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1995, it pioneered the hands-on simulation of a dinosaur dig, with its "The Big Dig".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Other permanent exhibits include "Secrets of the Diorama", an insight into what goes into a diorama, and "Science at the Academy", which showcases current Academy research.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The museum also has special, changing exhibits.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Recent changing exhibits include "Skin: Living Armor, Evolving Identity", "Illuminating Birds", "Extreme Deep: Mission to the Abyss", and "Crocs: Ancient Predators in a Modern World".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Four weekend festivals organized around scientific disciplines, are held during the year.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Paleopalooza, held in mid-February, features fossil collections and talks by leading paleontologists.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Earth Day Festival, held in mid-April, features scientists from the Academy's Patrick Center for Environmental Research.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Bug Fest, held in mid August, features entomologists, insect collections and live insects.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Philadelphia Shell Show, held in mid-October, features an international shell market and competitive shell displays.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy began offering lectures to the public as early as the 1820s.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Current offerings include natural history author talks, lectures by scientists, workshops and classes.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, the Center for Environmental Policy produces public programs on environmental issues.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Since its Nature Club in the 1930s, the Academy has offered programming just for children.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Several programs appropriate for different age groups are currently offered.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Safari Overnight sleepovers (camp-ins) are held on selected weekends during Fall, Winter, and Spring.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts can participate in day workshops and sleepovers to fulfill badge and pin requirements.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Tiny Tot Explorers is a program for toddlers.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] A new series of Family Workshops designed for both adults and children was launched in early 2010.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] "Wild Weekends", held on selected weekends throughout the year, offer a variety of children's programs, including hands-on exploration of museum specimens, crafts and live animal shows with mammals, birds and reptiles.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Live animal shows are also presented at regular times on other days and featured prominently in the educational programs.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Field trips to the Academy are available throughout the year for schools, summer camps and other groups.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Optional directed programs include Discovery Lessons for younger age groups (pre-K and higher) and Science Explorers for older children (grades 7 through 9).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] "Academy on the Go" is an educational outreach program that visits schools, camps, and community centers.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] WINS (Women in Natural Sciences) is an innovative and successful science enrichment program conducted by The Academy of Natural Sciences in collaboration with the School District of Philadelphia.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Since its founding in 1982, WINS has been providing female public school students with hands-on science classes, scientific literacy and skill-building activities, and opportunities for personal growth in a uniquely nurturing setting.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Academy Explorers Camp is a day camp program offered during Spring Break and the Summer.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The George Washington Carver Science Fair is held in February or March.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Science fair participants are eligible for the George Washington Carver Scholars summer program, which is also held at the Academy.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Educator workshops are held throughout the year.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The most recent series covered the integration of science and literacy skills.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Self-guided workbooks tailored for younger children are available for some of the museum exhibits.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Hayden Memorial Geological Award is given to prominent scientists working in geology or paleontology.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] It was established in 1888 in memory of Ferdinand V.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Hayden, a distinguished American geologist and pioneering surveyor of the American West who had extensive ties to the Academy.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Established in 1980, the Gold Medal for Distinction in Natural History Art is awarded to people whose artistic endeavors and life's work have contributed to our understanding and appreciation of living things.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Richard Hopper Day Memorial Medal, established in 1960 by his granddaughter, Margaret Day Dilks, is awarded in recognition of outstanding contributions in interpreting the natural sciences to the public.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Joseph Leidy Award honors research in the natural sciences.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] It was established in 1923 as a tribute to the many contributions and long association of Joseph Leidy with the Academy.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Böhlke Memorial Endowment Fund honors the memory of James E.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Böhlke who were prominent ichthyologists at the Academy.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] This fund provides support for graduate students and recent postdoctoral researchers to work with the Ichthyology Collection and the Academy's Library.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Gallagher Fellowship provides a unique opportunity for original, multi-year, postdoctoral or sabbatical research on the systematics of microscopic invertebrates, especially Rotifera.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The research focus must be on systematics and may employ ecological, behavioral, physiological, molecular or developmental tools.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] Jessup and McHenry Awards are competitively awarded to students wishing to conduct studies at the postgraduate, doctoral and postdoctoral levels under the supervision or sponsorship of a member of the curatorial staff of the Academy.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Jessup Award is given for any specialty in which our curators have expertise.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The McHenry Fund is restricted to botanists.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Eckelberry Endowment helps support the efforts of wildlife painters, sculptors, printmakers, and other artists to better acquaint themselves with the natural world through both museum and field research.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, artistic and scientific mentors counsel and assist these artists as their careers develop.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] Ajax is not a technology, but rather a programming pattern.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] HTML and CSS can be used in combination to mark up and style information.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] The webpage can be modified by JavaScript to dynamically display (and allow the user to interact with) the new information.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] The built-in XMLHttpRequest object is used to execute Ajax on webpages, allowing websites to load content onto the screen without refreshing the page.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] In the early-to-mid 1990s, most websites were based on complete HTML pages.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] Each user action required a complete new page to be loaded from the server.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] This process was inefficient, as reflected by the user experience: all page content disappeared, then the new page appeared.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] Each time the browser reloaded a page because of a partial change, all the content had to be re-sent, even though only some of the information had changed.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] This placed additional load on the server and made bandwidth a limiting factor in performance.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] The foundations of AJAX originate back in 1996 with the introduction of JavaScript 1.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] Developers quickly discovered that any HTML element which accepted a "src" attribute could be used to fetch remote data.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] By changing the src of a hidden frame, a developer could fetch remote data, process or display it without a page refresh.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] The remote data could be a string, JavaScript code, XML or a partial HTML page generated on the server.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] The same could be done with `<img>` and `<embed>` tags, but many developers were alarmed at the concept of an executable GIF and preferred to use the hidden `<iframe>`.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] This technique was used for both Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer, the two main browsers at the time, until developers discovered the XMLHTTP server object (MSXML 1.0) was included in Internet Explorer 4.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] Browser detection was then used to either implement the hidden `<iframe>` in Netscape or use the XMLHTTP (MSXML 1.0) object in IE 4.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] In 1996, the iframe tag was introduced by Internet Explorer; like the object element, it can load a part of the web page asynchronously.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] In 1998, the Microsoft Outlook Web Access team developed the concept behind the XMLHttpRequest scripting object.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] It appeared as XMLHTTP in the second version of the MSXML library, which shipped with Internet Explorer 5.0 in March 1999.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] The functionality of the Windows XMLHTTP ActiveX control in IE 5 was later implemented by Mozilla Firefox, Safari, Opera, Google Chrome, and other browsers as the XMLHttpRequest JavaScript object.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] Microsoft adopted the native XMLHttpRequest model as of Internet Explorer 7.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] Support for the ActiveX version remained in Internet Explorer and on "Internet Explorer mode" in Microsoft Edge.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] The utility of these background HTTP requests and asynchronous Web technologies remained fairly obscure until it started appearing in large scale online applications such as Outlook Web Access (2000) and Oddpost (2002).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] Google made a wide deployment of standards-compliant, cross browser Ajax with Gmail (2004) and Google Maps (2005).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] In October 2004 Kayak.com's public beta release was among the first large-scale e-commerce uses of what their developers at that time called "the xml http thing".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] This increased interest in Ajax among web program developers.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] The term *AJAX* was publicly used on 18 February 2005 by Jesse James Garrett in an article titled *Ajax: A New Approach to Web Applications*, based on techniques used on Google pages.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] On 5 April 2006, the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) released the first draft specification for the XMLHttpRequest object in an attempt to create an official Web standard.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] The latest draft of the XMLHttpRequest object was published on 6 October 2016, and the XMLHttpRequest specification is now a living standard.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] The term *Ajax* has come to represent a broad group of Web technologies that can be used to implement a Web application that communicates with a server in the background, without interfering with the current state of the page.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] Since then, however, there have been a number of developments in the technologies used in an Ajax application, and in the definition of the term Ajax itself.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] XML is no longer required for data interchange and, therefore, XSLT is no longer required for the manipulation of data.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) is often used as an alternative format for data interchange, although other formats such as preformatted HTML or plain text can also be used.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] A variety of popular JavaScript libraries, including jQuery, include abstractions to assist in executing Ajax requests.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] An example of a simple Ajax request using the GET method, written in JavaScript.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] Ajax offers several benefits that can significantly enhance web application performance and user experience.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] By reducing server traffic and improving speed, Ajax plays a crucial role in modern web development.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] One key advantage of Ajax is its capacity to render web applications without requiring data retrieval, resulting in reduced server traffic.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] This optimization minimizes response times on both the server and client sides, eliminating the need for users to endure loading screens.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] Furthermore, Ajax facilitates asynchronous processing by simplifying the utilization of XmlHttpRequest, which enables efficient handling of requests for asynchronous data retrieval.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] Additionally, the dynamic loading of content enhances the application's performance significantly.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/ajax] Besides, Ajax enjoys broad support across all major web browsers, including Microsoft Internet Explorer versions 5 and above, Mozilla Firefox versions 1.0 and beyond, Opera versions 7.6 and above, and Apple Safari versions 1.2 and higher.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] The **American Archive of Public Broadcasting** (**AAPB**) is a collaboration between the Library of Congress and WGBH Educational Foundation, founded through the efforts of the Corporation for Public Broadcasting (CPB).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] The AAPB is a national effort to digitally preserve and make accessible historically significant public radio and television programs created over the past 70+ years.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] The archive comprises over 120 collections from contributing stations and original producers from US states and territories.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] As of April 2020, the collection includes nearly 113,000 digitized items preserved on-site at the Library of Congress, and 53,000 items in the collection are streaming online in the AAPB Online Reading Room.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] Funders include the CPB, the Council on Library and Information Resources, and Institute of Museum and Library Services.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] The Corporation for Public Broadcasting (CPB) began inventorying US public media content in 2007.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] By 2013, 2.5 million items had been inventoried including 40,000 hours of broadcasting which was being digitized with funding from the CPB.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] An advisory council, which included Ken Burns, John W.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] Carlin, Henry Louis Gates Jr., Cokie Roberts, Stephen D.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] Smith, Margaret Spellings, Howard Stringer, and Jesús Salvador Treviño, recommended that a collaboration between WGBH and the Library of Congress form and operate the archive.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] In the first phase of the project, which began in 2013, the Archive will complete the digitization of 40,000 hours of radio and television programs and select an additional 5,000 hours of born-digital programs to be included in the collection.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] The collection will be made available to the public on-site in Washington, D.C. and in Boston.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] A rights clearance strategy will be developed to comply with legal restrictions, including copyright law and a website will provide public access to much of the collection.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] Programs from National Educational Television (NET), which operated from 1952 through 1972, are being cataloged in a project scheduled to be completed in 2018.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] 8,000–10,000 NET titles are expected to be cataloged and an incomplete preliminary list is currently online.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] The PBS NewsHour Digitization Project has made more than 13,500 episodes of *PBS NewsHour* and its predecessor programs available online.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] Transcripts of over 9,000 shows (1975–2015) will also be made available.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] The Public Broadcasting Preservation Fellowship (PBPF) began in 2018 and supports graduate students enrolled in non-specialized programs to pursue digital preservation projects at public broadcasting organizations around the country.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] In 2020, the University of Alabama partnered with WGBH to adopt and launch its model of the PBPF program, providing both local and remote students enrolled in the University of Alabama's School of Library and Information Studies with opportunities to pursue Fellowships at stations in their area.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] In 2021, the AAPB launched the “Presenting the Past" podcast series in collaboration with the Society for Cinema and Media Studies (SCMS).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] The series features informed conversations with scholars, educators, industry professionals, researchers, archivists, and others about significant events, issues, and topics documented in the AAPB collections.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] The AAPB Special Collections include notable selections of public radio and television content with a specified search bar for items within the collection, a detailed summary of the content, and related resources.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-archive-of-public-broadcasting] In the AAPB curated Exhibits, curators select primary and secondary source recordings to present a diversity of perspectives concerning the exhibit's focus.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The **American Museum of Natural History** (**AMNH**) is a natural history museum on the Upper West Side of Manhattan in New York City.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Located in Theodore Roosevelt Park, across the street from Central Park, the museum complex comprises 21 interconnected buildings housing 45 permanent exhibition halls, in addition to a planetarium and a library.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] AMNH has a full-time scientific staff of 225, sponsors over 120 special field expeditions each year, and averages about five million visits annually.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The AMNH is a private 501(c)(3) organization.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Bickmore devised the idea for the American Museum of Natural History in 1861, and, after several years of advocacy, the museum opened within Central Park's Arsenal on May 22, 1871.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's first purpose-built structure in Theodore Roosevelt Park was designed by Calvert Vaux and J.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Wrey Mould and opened on December 22, 1877.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Numerous wings have been added over the years, including the main entrance pavilion (named for Theodore Roosevelt) in 1936 and the Rose Center for Earth and Space in 2000.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Bickmore devised the idea for the American Museum of Natural History in 1861.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] At the time, he was studying in Cambridge, Massachusetts, at Louis Agassiz's Museum of Comparative Zoology.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Upon the end of the American Civil War, Bickmore asked numerous prominent New Yorkers, such as William E.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Although Dodge himself could not fund the museum at the time, he introduced the naturalist to Theodore Roosevelt Sr., the father of future U.S. president Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Calls for a natural history museum increased after Barnum's American Museum burned down in 1868.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Eighteen prominent New Yorkers wrote a letter to the Central Park Commission that December, requesting the creation of a natural history museum in Central Park.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Central Park commissioner Andrew Haswell Green indicated his support for the project in January 1869.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] A board of trustees was created for the museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The next month, Bickmore and Joseph Hodges Choate drafted a charter for the museum, which the board of trustees approved without any changes.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It was in this charter that the "American Museum of Natural History" name was first used.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Bickmore said he wanted the museum's name to reflect his "expectation that our museum will ultimately become the leading institution of its kind in our country", similar to the British Museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Before the museum was established, Bickmore needed to secure approval from Boss Tweed, leader of the powerful and corrupt Tammany Hall political organization.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The legislation to establish the American Museum of Natural History had to be signed by John Thompson Hoffman, the governor of New York, who was associated with Tweed.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Hoffman signed the legislation creating the museum on April 6, 1869, with John David Wolfe as its first president.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Subsequently, the chairman of the AMNH's executive committee asked Green if the museum could use the top two stories of Central Park's Arsenal, and Green approved the request in January 1870.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Insect specimens were placed on the lower level of the Arsenal, while stones, fossils, mammals, birds, fish, and reptiles were placed on the upper level.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum opened within the Arsenal on May 22, 1871.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The AMNH became popular in the following years.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Arsenal location had 856,773 visitors in the first nine months of 1876 alone, more than the British Museum had recorded for all of 1874.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Meanwhile, the AMNH's directors had identified Manhattan Square (bounded by Eighth Avenue/Central Park West, 81st Street, Ninth Avenue/Columbus Avenue, and 77th Street) as a site for a permanent structure.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Several prominent New Yorkers had raised $500,000 to fund the construction of the new building.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The city's park commissioners then reserved Manhattan Square as the site of the permanent museum, and another $200,000 was raised for the building fund.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Numerous dignitaries and officials, including U.S. president Ulysses S.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Grant, attended the museum's groundbreaking ceremony on June 3, 1874.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum opened on December 22, 1877, with a ceremony attended by U.S. president Rutherford B.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The old exhibits were removed from the Arsenal in 1878, and the AMNH was debt-free by the next year.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Originally, the AMNH was accessed by a temporary bridge that crossed a ditch, and it was closed during Sundays.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's trustees voted in May 1881 to complete the approaches from Central Park, and work began later that year.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The landscape changes were nearly complete by mid-1882, and a bridge over Central Park West opened that November.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] At this point, the AMNH's Manhattan Square building and the Arsenal could not physically fit any more objects, and the existing facilities, such as the 100-seat lecture hall, were insufficient to accommodate demand.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The trustees began discussing the possibility of opening the museum on Sundays in May 1885, and the state legislature approved a bill permitting Sunday operations the next year.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Despite advocacy from the working class, the trustees opposed Sunday operations because it would be expensive to do so.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] At the time, the museum was open to the general public on Wednesdays through Saturdays, and it was open exclusively to members on Mondays and Tuesdays.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's collections continued to grow during the 1880s, and it hosted various lectures through the 19th century.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] With several departments having been crowded out of the original building, New York state legislators introduced bills to expand the AMNH in early 1887; thousands of teachers endorsed the legislation.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Kellogg was directed to prepare plans for landscaping the site.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In March 1888, the trustees approved an entrance pavilion at the center of the 77th Street elevation.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The New York City Board of Estimate began soliciting bids from general contractors in late 1889.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Many of the objects and specimens in the museum's collection could not be displayed until the annex was opened.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The original building was refurbished during 1890, and the museum's library was transferred to the west wing that year.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The AMNH's trustees considered opening the museum on Sundays by February 1892 and stopped charging admission that July.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum began Sunday operations in August, and the southern entrance pavilion opened that November.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Even with the new wing, there was still not enough space for the museum's collection.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The city's Park Board approved a new lecture hall in January 1893, but the hall was postponed that May in favor of a wing extending east on 77th Street.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] A contract to furnish the east wing was awarded in June 1894.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] When the east wing was nearly completed in February 1895, the AMNH's trustees asked state legislators for $200,000 to build a wing extending west on 77th Street.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The east wing was still being furnished by August; its ground floor opened that December.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's funds and collections continued to grow during this time.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] A hall of mammals opened within the museum in November 1896.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] That year, the AMNH received approval to extend the east wing northward along Central Park West, creating an L-shaped structure.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Plans for an expanded east wing were approved in June 1897, and a contract was awarded two months later.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Jesup also sponsored worldwide expeditions to obtain objects for the collection.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] By mid-1898, the west wing, the expanded east wing, and a lecture hall at the center of the museum were underway; however, the project encountered delays due to a lack of city funding.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The west and east wings, with several exhibit halls, were nearly complete by late 1899, but the lecture hall had been delayed.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] A hall dedicated to ancient Mexican art opened that December.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's 1,350-seat lecture hall opened in October 1900, as did the Native American and Mexican halls in the west wing.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] During the 1900s, the AMNH sponsored several expeditions to grow its collection, including a trip to Mexico, a trip to collect fauna from the Pacific Northwest, a trip to collect art in China, and an expedition to collect rocks in local caves.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] One such exhibition yielded a brontosaurus skeleton, which was the centerpiece of the dinosaur hall that opened in February 1905.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In the early 1920s, museum president Henry Fairfield Osborn planned a new entrance for the AMNH, which was to contain a memorial to Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Also around that time, the New York state government formed a commission to study the feasibility of a Roosevelt memorial.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] After a dispute over whether to put the memorial in Albany or in New York City, the government of New York City offered a site next to the AMNH for consideration.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The commission rejected a "conventional Greek mausoleum" design, instead opting to design a triumphal arch and hall in a Roman style.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 1925, the AMNH's trustees hosted an architectural design competition, selecting John Russell Pope to design the memorial hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Construction began in 1929, and the trustees approved final plans the next year.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Harry McNally was the general contractor.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Roosevelt's cousin, U.S. president Franklin D.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Roosevelt, dedicated the memorial on January 19, 1936.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The original building was later known as "Wing A".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] During the 1950s, the top floor was renovated into a library, being redecorated with what Christopher Gray of *The New York Times* described as "dropped ceilings and the other usual insults".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The ten-story Childs Frick Building, which contained the AMNH's fossil collection, was added to the museum in the 1970s.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The architect Kevin Roche and his firm Roche-Dinkeloo have been responsible for the master planning of the museum since the 1990s.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Various renovations to both the interior and exterior have been carried out.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Renovations to the Dinosaur Hall were undertaken beginning in 1991, and Roche-Dinkeloo designed the eight-story AMNH Library in 1992.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's Rose Center for Earth and Space was completed in 2000.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 2001, the museum's lecture hall was renamed the Samuel J. and Ethel LeFrak Theater, after Samuel J.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] LeFrak donated US$8 million to the AMNH.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's south facade, spanning 77th Street from Central Park West to Columbus Avenue, was cleaned and repaired, re-emerging in 2009.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Steven Reichl, a spokesman for the museum, said that work would include restoring 650 black-cherry window frames and stone repairs.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's consultant on the latest renovation was Wiss, Janney, Elstner Associates, Inc., an architectural and engineering firm with headquarters in Northbrook, Illinois.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum also restored the mural in Roosevelt Memorial Hall in 2010.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 2026, the AMNH received $2 million to help fund the renovation of the Pacific Birds Hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 2014, the museum published plans for a $325 million, 195,000 ft2 (18,100 m2) annex, the Richard Gilder Center for Science, Education, and Innovation, on the Columbus Avenue side.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It was named after stockbroker and philanthropist Richard Gilder.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] On October 11, 2016, the Landmarks Preservation Commission unanimously approved the expansion.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Construction of the Gilder Center, which was expected to break ground the next year following design development and Environmental Impact Statement stages, would entail demolition of three museum buildings built between 1874 and 1935.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum filed plans for the expansion in August 2017, but due to community opposition, construction did not start until June 2019.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] On May 4, 2023, the Gilder Center opened, and the museum had 1.5 million visitors over the next three months.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 2025, the AMNH began providing free "Discoverer" memberships to Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program recipients.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In late 2023, the museum announced that it would stop displaying human remains from its collection.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Despite the 1990 passage of the Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act (NAGPRA), as late as 2023, the AMNH held an estimated 1,900 Native American remains that had not been repatriated.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In January 2024, the museum closed a number of displays and the AMNH's Eastern Woodlands and Great Plains halls, or about 10,000 square feet.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum agreed to repatriate the remains that July.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The original Victorian Gothic building was designed by Calvert Vaux and J.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Wrey Mould, both already closely identified with the architecture of Central Park.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Vaux and Mould's original plan was intended to complement the Metropolitan Museum of Art on the opposite side of Central Park.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The original building, as constructed, was at the center of the 77th Street frontage and measured 199 by 66 feet (61 by 20 m) across; it featured a gallery measuring 112 feet (34 m) long200 ft (61 m) tall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] This gallery contained a raised basement, three stories of exhibits, Venetian Gothic arches, and an attic with dormers and a slate roof.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The rear of the gallery included two towers: one containing a stairwell and the other containing curators' rooms.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The original structure still exists but is hidden from view by the many buildings in the complex that today occupy most of Manhattan Square.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum remains accessible through its 77th Street foyer, which has since been renamed the Grand Gallery.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The full plan called for twelve pavilions similar in design to the original building.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Eight pavilions would have been arranged as the sides of a square, while the remaining four would be perpendicular to each other in the interior of the square.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] There were to be eight towers along the perimeter of the square, as well as a 120 ft-wide (37 m) dome in the center, at the intersection of the four interior pavilions.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In each pavilion, there was to be a ground floor; the second floor was to contain a gallery; the third floor was to exhibit specimens; and the fourth floor was to be used for research.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Upon the intended completion of the master plan, the museum would measure 850 ft (260 m) from north to south and 650 ft (200 m) from west to east, including projections from the square.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The finished structure, with a ground area of over 18 acres (7.3 ha), would have been the largest building in North America, as well as the largest museum building in the world.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The master plan was never fully realized; by 2015, the museum consisted of 25 separate buildings that were poorly connected.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The original building was soon eclipsed by the west and east wings of the southern frontage, designed by J.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Cleaveland Cady as a brownstone neo-Romanesque structure.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It extends 700 ft (210 m) along West 77th Street, with corner towers 150 ft (46 m) tall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Its pink brownstone and granite, similar to that found at Grindstone Island in the St.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Lawrence River, came from quarries at Picton Island, New York.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The southern wing contains several halls ranging in size from 60 by 110 feet (18 m × 34 m) to 30 ft × 125 ft (9.1 m × 38.1 m).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] At the ends of either wings are rounded turret-like towers.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The main entrance hall on Central Park West is formally known as the **New York State Memorial to Theodore Roosevelt**.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Completed by John Russell Pope in 1936, it is an over-scaled Beaux-Arts monument to former U.S. president Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall was originally supposed to have formed one end of an "Intermuseum Promenade" through Central Park, connecting with the Metropolitan Museum of Art to the east, but the promenade was never completed.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The memorial hall has a pink-granite facade, which is modeled after Roman arches.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In front of the hall on Central Park West is a terrace measuring 350 ft (110 m) long, as well as a series of steps.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The main entrance consists of an arch measuring 60 ft (18 m) high.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The underside of the arch is a coffered granite vestibule, which leads to a bronze, glass, and marble screen.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It is flanked by two pairs of columns, which are topped by figures of American explorers John James Audubon, Daniel Boone, Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] These figures were sculpted by James Earle Fraser and are about 30 ft (9.1 m) high.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In the attic above the main archway, there is an inscription describing Roosevelt's accomplishments.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The words "Truth", "Knowledge", and "Vision" are carved into the entablature under this inscription.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Fraser also designed an equestrian statue of Theodore Roosevelt, flanked by a Native American and an African American, which originally stood outside the memorial hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In the 21st century, the statue generated controversy due to its subordinate depiction of these figures behind Roosevelt.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] This prompted AMNH officials to announce in 2020 that they would remove the statue.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The statue was removed in January 2022 and will be on a long-term loan to the Theodore Roosevelt Presidential Library in North Dakota.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The interior of the Memorial Hall measures 67 by 120 ft (20 by 37 m) across, with a barrel-vaulted ceiling measuring 100 ft (30 m) tall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The ceiling contains octagonal coffers, while the floors are made of mosaic marble tiles.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The lowest 9 ft (2.7 m) of the walls are wainscoted in marble, above which the walls of the memorial hall are made of limestone.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The top of each wall contains a marble band and a Corinthian entablature.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Each of the Memorial Hall's four sides contains two red-marble columns, each measuring 48 ft (15 m) tall and rising from a Botticino marble pedestal.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] There are rounded windows at clerestory level on the north and south walls.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] William Andrew MacKay designed three 62 ft-wide (19 m) murals depicting important events in Roosevelt's life: the construction of the Panama Canal on the north wall, African exploration on the west wall, and the Treaty of Portsmouth on the south wall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The east and west walls, contain four quotes from Roosevelt under the headings "Nature", "Manhood", "Youth", and "The State".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Memorial Hall originally connected to various classrooms, exhibition rooms, and a 600-person auditorium.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Directly underneath the Memorial Hall is an entrance to the 81st Street–Museum of Natural History station.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Today, the hall connects to the Akeley Hall of African Mammals and the Hall of Asian Mammals.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Memorial Hall contains four exhibits that describe Theodore Roosevelt's conservation activities in his youth, early adulthood, U.S. presidency, and post-presidency.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Named after taxidermist Carl Akeley, the Akeley Hall of African Mammals is a two-story hall on the second floor, directly west of the Theodore Roosevelt Memorial Hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It connects to the Hall of African Peoples to the west.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of African Mammals' 28 dioramas depict in meticulous detail the great range of ecosystems found in Africa and the mammals endemic to them.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The centerpiece of the hall is a herd of eight African elephants in a characteristic 'alarmed' formation.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Though the mammals are typically the main feature in the dioramas, birds and flora of the regions are occasionally featured as well.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall in its current form was completed in 1936.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of African Mammals was first proposed to the museum by Carl Akeley around 1909; he proposed 40 dioramas featuring the rapidly vanishing landscapes and animals of Africa.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Daniel Pomeroy, a trustee of the museum and partner at J.P.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Morgan & Co., offered investors the opportunity to accompany the museum's expeditions in Africa in exchange for funding.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Akeley began collecting specimens for the hall as early as 1909, famously encountering Theodore Roosevelt in the midst of the Smithsonian-Roosevelt African expedition.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] On these early expeditions, Akeley was accompanied by his former apprentice in taxidermy, James L.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] When Akeley returned to Africa to collect gorillas for the hall's first diorama, Clark remained behind and began scouring the country for artists to create the backgrounds.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The eventual appearance of the first habitat groups impacted the design of other diorama halls, including Birds of the World, the Hall of North American Mammals, the Vernay Hall of Southeast Asian Mammals, and the Hall of Oceanic Life.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] After Akeley's unexpected death during the Eastman-Pomeroy expedition in 1926, responsibility of the hall's completion fell to James L.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Clark, who hired architectural artist James Perry Wilson in 1933 to assist Leigh in the painting of backgrounds.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Wilson made many improvements on Leigh's techniques, including a range of methods to minimize the distortion caused by the dioramas' curved walls.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 1936, William Durant Campbell, a wealthy board member with a desire to see Africa, offered to fund several dioramas if allowed to obtain the specimens himself.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Clark agreed to this arrangement, resulting in the acquisition of numerous large specimens.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Kane joined Leigh, Wilson, and several other artists in completing the hall's remaining dioramas.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Though construction of the hall was completed in 1936, the dioramas gradually opened between the mid-1920s and early 1940s.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of Asian Mammals, sometimes referred to as the Vernay-Faunthorpe Hall of Asian Mammals, is directly south of the Theodore Roosevelt Memorial Hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It contains 8 complete dioramas, 4 partial dioramas, and 6 habitat groups of mammals and locations from India, Nepal, Burma, and Malaysia.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall opened in 1930 and, similar to the Akeley Hall of African Mammals, is centered around 2 Asian elephants.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] At one point, a giant panda and Siberian tiger were also part of the Hall's collection, originally intended to be part of an adjoining Hall of North Asian Mammals (planned in the current location of Stout Hall of Asian Peoples).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] These specimens can currently be seen in the Hall of Biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Specimens for the Hall of Asian Mammals were collected over six expeditions led by British-born antiques dealer Arthur S.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] John Faunthorpe (as noted by stylized plaques at both entrances).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The expeditions were funded entirely by Vernay, who characterized the expense as a British tribute to American involvement in World War I.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The first Vernay-Faunthorpe expedition took place in 1922, when many of the animals Vernay was seeking, such as the Sumatran rhinoceros and Asiatic lion, were facing the possibility of extinction.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Vernay made many appeals to regional authorities to obtain hunting permits; in later museum-related expeditions headed by Vernay, these appeals helped the museum gain access to areas previously restricted to foreign visitors.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Rosenkranz accompanied the Vernay-Faunthorpe expeditions as field artist and painted the majority of the diorama backgrounds in the hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] These expeditions were also well documented in both photo and video, with enough footage of the first expedition to create a feature-length film, *Hunting Tigers in India* (1929).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Bernard Family Hall of North American Mammals is on the first floor, directly west of the Theodore Roosevelt Memorial Hall. features 43 dioramas of various mammals of the American continent, north of tropical Mexico.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Each diorama places focus on a particular species, ranging from the largest megafauna to the smaller rodents and carnivorans.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Notable dioramas include the Alaskan brown bears looking at a salmon after they scared off an otter, a pair of wolves, a pair of Sonoran jaguars, and dueling bull Alaska moose.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of North American Mammals opened in 1942 with only ten dioramas.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] A massive restoration project began in late 2011 following a large donation from Jill and Lewis Bernard.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In October 2012 the hall was reopened as the Bernard Hall of North American Mammals.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of Small Mammals is an offshoot of the Bernard Family Hall of North American Mammals, directly to the west of the latter.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] There are several small dioramas featuring small mammals found throughout North America, including collared peccaries, Abert's squirrel, and a wolverine.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Sanford Hall of North American birds is a one-story hall on the third floor, between the Hall of Primates and Akeley Hall's second level.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] There are over 20 dioramas depicting birds from across North America in their native habitats.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] At the far end of the hall is an old mural of pink flamingos by ornithologist and artist Louis Agassiz Fuertes.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall also has display cases devoted to large collections of warblers, owls, and raptors.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Conceived by museum ornithologist Frank Chapman, the Hall is named for Chapman's friend and amateur ornithologist Leonard C.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Sanford, who partially funded the hall and also donated the entirety of his own bird specimen collection to the museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Construction began on the hall's dioramas as early as 1902, and the dioramas opened in 1909.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] They were the first to be exhibited in the museum and are the oldest still on display.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Although Chapman was not the first to create museum dioramas, he was the first to bring artists into the field with him in the hopes of capturing a specific location at a specific time.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In contrast to the dramatic scenes that Akeley created for the African Hall, Chapman wanted his dioramas to evoke a scientific realism, ultimately serving as a historical record of habitats and species facing a high probability of extinction.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Each of Chapman's dioramas depicted a species, their nests, and 4 ft (1.2 m) of the surrounding habitat in each direction.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of Birds of the World is on the south side of the second floor.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The global diversity of bird species is exhibited in this hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] 12 dioramas showcase various ecosystems around the world and provide a sample of the varieties of birds that live there.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Example dioramas include South Georgia featuring king penguins and skuas, the East African plains featuring secretarybirds and bustards, and the Australian outback featuring honeyeaters, cockatoos, and kookaburras.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Whitney Memorial Wing, originally named after Harry Payne Whitney and comprising 750,000 birds, opened in 1939.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Later known as the Hall of Oceanic Birds, it was completed and dedicated in 1953.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It was founded by Frank Chapman and Leonard C.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Sanford, originally museum volunteers, who had gone forward with creation of a hall to feature birds of the Pacific islands.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall was designed as a completely immersive collection of dioramas, including a circular display featuring birds-of-paradise.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 1998, the Butterfly Conservatory was installed inside the hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of Reptiles and Amphibians is near the southeast corner of the third floor.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It serves as an introduction to herpetology, with many exhibits detailing reptile evolution, anatomy, diversity, reproduction, and behavior.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Notable exhibits include a Komodo dragon group, an American alligator, Lonesome George, the last Pinta Island tortoise, and poison dart frogs.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Defosse, and Emmett Reid Dunn collected specimens of the Komodo Dragon for the museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Burden's chapter "The Komodo Dragon", in *Look to the Wilderness*, describes the expedition, the habitat, and the behavior of the dragon.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall opened in 1927 and was rebuilt from 1969 to 1977 at a cost of $1.3 million.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of Biodiversity is underneath the Theodore Roosevelt Memorial Hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall primarily contains exhibits and objects highlighting the concept of biodiversity, the interactions between living organisms, and the negative impacts of extinction on biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall includes a 2,500 ft2 (230 m2) diorama depicting the Dzanga-Sangha Special Reserve rainforest with over 160 animal and plant species.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The diorama shows the rainforest in three states: pristine, altered by human activity, and destroyed by human activity.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Another attraction in the hall is "The Spectrum of Habitats", a video wall displaying footage of nine ecosystems.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] There is a "Transformation Wall", containing information and stories detailing changes to biodiversity, and a "Solutions Wall", containing suggestions on how to increase biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of North American Forests is a one-story hall on the museum's first floor in between the Theodore Roosevelt Memorial Hall and the Warburg Hall of New York State Environments.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It contains ten dioramas depicting a range of forest types from across North America as well as several displays on forest conservation and tree health.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall was constructed under the guidance of botanist Henry K.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Each diorama specifically lists both the location and exact time of year depicted.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Trees and plants featured in the dioramas are constructed of a combination of art supplies and actual bark and other specimens collected in the field.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The entrance to the hall features a cross section from the Mark Twain Tree, 1,400-year-old sequoia taken from the King's River grove on the west flank of the Sierra Mountains in 1891.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Warburg Hall of New York State Environments is a one-story hall on the museum's ground floor in between the Hall of North American Forests and the Grand Hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Based on the town of Pine Plains in Dutchess County, New York, the hall gives a multi-faceted presentation of the eco-systems typical of New York.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Aspects covered include soil types, seasonal changes, and the impact of both humans and nonhuman animals on the environment.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It is named for the German-American philanthropist Felix M.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Warburg and opened on May 14, 1951, as the Warburg Memorial Hall of General Ecology.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It has changed little since and is now frequently regarded for its retro-modern styling.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Milstein Hall of Ocean Life is in the southeastern quadrant of the first floor, west of the Hall of Biodiversity.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It focuses on marine biology, botany and marine conservation.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The center of the hall contains a 94 ft (29 m)-long blue whale model.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The upper level of the hall exhibits the vast array of ecosystems present in the ocean.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Dioramas compare and contrast the life in these different settings including kelp forests, mangroves, coral reefs, the bathypelagic, among others.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It attempts to show how vast and varied the oceans are while encouraging common themes throughout.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The lower half of the hall consists of 15 large dioramas of larger marine organisms.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It is on this level that the famous "Squid and the Whale" diorama sits, depicting a hypothetical fight between the two creatures.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Other notable exhibits in this hall include the two-level Andros Coral Reef Diorama.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Osborn proposed the construction of a large building in the museum's southeast courtyard to house a new Hall of Ocean Life in which "models and skeletons of whales" would be exhibited.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall opened in 1924 and was renovated in 1962.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 1969, a renovation gave the hall a more explicit focus on oceanic megafauna, including the addition of a lifelike blue whale model to replace a popular steel and papier-mâché whale model that had hung in the Biology of Mammals hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Richard Van Gelder oversaw the creation of the hall in its current incarnation.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall was renovated once again in 2003, this time with environmentalism and conservation being the main focal points, and was renamed after developer Paul Milstein and AMNH board member Irma Milstein.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The 2003 renovation included refurbishment of the famous blue whale, suspended high above the 19,000 ft2 (1,800 m2) exhibit floor; updates to the 1930s and 1960s dioramas; and electronic displays.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Stout Hall of Asian Peoples is a one-story hall on the museum's second floor in between the Hall of Asian Mammals and Birds of the World.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Stout, a former president of the museum, and was primarily organized by Walter A.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Fairservis, a longtime museum archaeologist.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Opened in 1980, Stout Hall is the museum's largest anthropological hall and contains artifacts acquired by the museum between 1869 and the mid-1970s.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Many famous expeditions sponsored by the museum are associated with the artifacts in the hall, including the Roy Chapman Andrews expeditions in Central Asia and the Vernay-Hopwood Chindwin expedition.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Stout Hall has two sections: Ancient Eurasia, a small section devoted to the evolution of human civilization in Eurasia, and Traditional Asia, a much larger section containing cultural artifacts from across the Asian continent.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The latter section is organized to geographically correspond with two major trade routes of the Silk Road.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Like many of the museum's exhibition halls, the artifacts in Stout Hall are presented in a variety of ways including exhibits, miniature dioramas, and five full-scale dioramas.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Notable exhibits in the Ancient Eurasian section include reproductions from the archaeological sites of Teshik-Tash and Çatalhöyük, as well as a full size replica of a Hammurabi Stele.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Traditional Asia section contains areas devoted to major Asian countries, such as Japan, China, Tibet, and India, while also including a vast array of smaller Asian tribes including the Ainu, Semai, and Yakut.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall of African Peoples is behind Akeley Hall of African Mammals and underneath Sanford Hall of North American Birds.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It is organized by the four major ecosystems found in Africa: River Valley, Grasslands, Forest-Woodland, and Desert.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Each section presents artifacts and exhibits of the peoples native to the ecosystems throughout Africa.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall contains three dioramas and notable exhibits include a large collection of spiritual costumes on display in the Forest-Woodland section.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Uniting the sections of the hall is a multi-faceted comparison of African societies based on hunting and gathering, cultivation, and animal domestication.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Each type of society is presented in a historical, political, spiritual, and ecological context.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] A small section of African diaspora spread by the slave trade is also included.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall of Mexico and Central America is a one-story hall on the museum's second floor behind Birds of the World and before the Hall of South American Peoples.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It presents archaeological artifacts from a broad range of pre-Columbian civilizations that once existed across Mesoamerica, including the Maya, Olmec, Zapotec, and Aztec.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Because the great majority of the written records of these civilizations did not survive the Spanish conquest, the overarching aim of the hall is to piece together what it is possible to know about them from the artifacts alone.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The museum has displayed pre-Columbian artifacts since its opening, only a short time after the discovery of the civilizations by archaeologists, with its first hall dedicated to the subject opening in 1899.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] As the museum's collection grew, the hall underwent major renovations in 1944 and again in 1970 when it re-opened in its current form.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Notable artifacts on display include the Kunz Axe and a full-scale replica of Tomb 104 from the Monte Albán archaeological site, originally displayed at the 1939 World's Fair.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall of South American Peoples is a one-story hall on the northwestern corner of the second floor, next to the Hall of Mexico and Central America.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall was first opened on the third floor in 1904, and exhibited archaeological objects, including mummies, from Peru, Colombia, Bolivia, and the West Indies.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In 1931, the hall was expanded and relocated to the second floor under the direction of curators Ronald Olson and W.C.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The new hall included a recreation of a Chilean copper mine, and later, a temporary hall titled the Men of the Montaña, which featured Peruvian cultural artifacts from the Cashibo, and Panoan peoples.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In 1989, the Hall was renovated and reopened as a permanent exhibition, focusing on the technology and artistry of the ancient Andean and traditional Amazonian cultures, led by curators Craig Morris, Junius Bird, and Robert Carneiro.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall contains roughly 2,300 objects from various ancient South American cultures, including the Moche, Chávin, Chancay, Paracas, Nazca, and Inca.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] A number of the artifacts on display come from the Roosevelt Collections, which were collected by Theodore Roosevelt on expeditions to South America in the early 20th century and donated to the museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall of Pacific Peoples is on the southwestern corner of the third floor, accessed through the Hall of Plains Indians.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The cultural anthropologist Margaret Mead had founded the Hall of Pacific Peoples in 1971.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] From the time Mead began curatorial work on the hall in 1945, she conceived an exhibit environment that would emulate sights and sounds from the Pacific regions on display.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] After Mead's death in 1978, the hall reopened in December 1984 as the Margaret Mead Hall of Pacific Peoples.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The new hall, designed by Eugene Burgmann, maintained the blue-themed ocean and sky ambiance of the original hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall was once again closed in 1997 and reopened in 2001 with an updated design that retained the geocultural "alcoves" first installed with the 1984 remodel.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Margaret Mead Hall of Pacific Peoples contains artifacts from New Zealand, Australia, Indonesia, the Philippines, Micronesia, Melanesia and other Pacific islands.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Mead had collected 250 of the 1,500 items in the hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Some of these were probably selected from the 3,284 items she collected for the American Museum of Natural History during fieldwork in New Guinea and other Pacific island locations, 1928–1939.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Others, such as the theatrical set from a puppet play in Bali, were chosen from among the approximately 600 items that Mead and her anthropologist husband Gregory Bateson had sent to the American Museum of Natural History while they were conducting fieldwork in Bali, 1936–1938.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The exhibits in the Margaret Mead Hall of Pacific Peoples also include a fiberglass cast of an Easter Island *moai* statue and capes made of honeycreeper feathers.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Northwest Coast Hall is a one-story hall on the museum's ground floor behind the Grand Gallery and in between Warburg and Spitzer Halls. it is the museum's oldest hall, having been established in 1899 by anthropologist Franz Boas as the Jesup North Pacific Hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall now contains artifacts and exhibits of the tribes of the North Pacific Coast cultural region (Southern Alaska, Northern Washington, and a portion of British Columbia).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Featured prominently in the hall are four "House Posts" from the Kwakwaka'wakw nation and murals by William S.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] As of 2022, there are 9,000 items in total, including 78 totem poles, as well as a Haida canoe suspended from the ceiling (relocated from the Grand Gallery in 2020).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The artifacts are accompanied by text in numerous Native American languages.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Artifacts in the hall originated from three main sources.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The earliest of these was a gift of Haida artifacts collected by John Wesley Powell and donated by future trustee Heber R.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] This was followed by the museum's purchase of two collections of Tlingit artifacts collected by Lt.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The remainder of the hall's artifacts were collected during the famed Jesup North Pacific Expedition between 1897 and 1902.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Led by Boas and financed by museum president Morris Ketchum Jesup, the expedition was the first for the museum's Division of Anthropology and is now considered the "foremost expedition in American anthropology".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Many famous ethnologists took part, including George Hunt, who secured the Kwakwaka'wakw House Posts in the hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Other tribes featured in the hall include Coastal Salish, Nuu-chah-nulth, Tsimshian, and Nuxalk.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] At the time of its opening, the Northwest Coast Hall was one of four halls dedicated to the native peoples of United States and Canada.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It was originally organized in two sections, the first being a general area pertaining to all peoples of the region and the second a specialized area divided by tribe.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] This was a point of contention for Boas who wanted all artifacts in the hall to be associated with the proper tribe (much like it is currently organized), eventually leading to the dissolution of Boas's relationship with the museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In May 2022, the hall reopened after a five-year, $19 million renovation, with more than 1,000 artifacts on view.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The new display includes work from contemporary artists such as Greg Colfax KlaWayHee and Robert Davidson.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall of Plains Indians is on the south side of the third floor, near the western end of the museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The primary focus of this hall is the North American Great Plains peoples as they were at the middle of the 19th century, including depictions of Blackfeet (*see also: Blackfoot Confederacy*), Hidatsa, and Dakota cultures.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Of particular interest is a Folsom point discovered in 1926 New Mexico, providing evidence of early American colonization of the Americas.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall of Eastern Woodlands Indians is next to the Hall of Plains Indians, on the south side of the third floor.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It details the lives and technology of traditional Native American peoples in the woodland environments of eastern North America.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] These include Cree, Mohegan, Ojibwe, and Iroquois cultures.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The exhibit features examples of indigenous basketry, pottery, farming techniques, food preparation, metal jewelry, musical instruments, and textiles.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Other highlights include a model of a Menominee birchbark canoe and various traditional lodgings such as an Ojibwa domed wigwam, an Iroquois longhouse, a Creek council house, and other eastern woodland dwelling styles.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] As of January 2024, the Hall of Eastern Woodlands Indians, along with the Hall of the Plains Indians, is closed to ensure compliance with new NAGPRA regulations.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Anne and Bernard Spitzer Hall of Human Origins, formerly The Hall of Human Biology and Evolution, is on the south side of the first floor, near the western end of the museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It opened under its current name on February 10, 2007.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] When it first opened in 1921, the hall was known as the "Hall of the Age of Man", the only major exhibition in the United States to present an in-depth investigation of human evolution.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The displays traced the story of *Homo sapiens*, illuminated the path of human evolution and examined the origins of human creativity.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Many of the displays from the original hall can still be viewed in the present expanded format.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] These include life-size dioramas of human predecessors *Australopithecus afarensis*, *Homo ergaster*, Neanderthal, and Cro-Magnon, showing each species demonstrating the behaviors and capabilities that scientists believe they were capable of.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Also displayed are full-sized casts of important fossils, including the 3.2-million-year-old Lucy skeleton and the 1.7-million-year-old Turkana Boy, and *Homo erectus* specimens including a cast of Peking Man.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall also features replicas of ice age art found in the Dordogne region of southwestern France.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The limestone carvings of horses were made nearly 26,000 years ago and are considered to represent some of the earliest artistic expression of humans.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Arthur Ross Hall of Meteorites is on the southwest corner of the first floor.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It contains some of the finest specimens in the world including Ahnighito, a section of the 200-ton Cape York meteorite which was first made known to non-Inuit cultures on their investigation of Meteorite Island, Greenland.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Its great weight, 34 tons, makes it the largest displayed in the Northern Hemisphere.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It has support by columns that extend through the floor and into the bedrock below the museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall also contains extra-solar nanodiamonds (diamonds with dimensions on the nanometer level) more than 5 billion years old.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] These were extracted from a meteorite sample through chemical means, and they are so small that a quadrillion of these fit into a volume smaller than a cubic centimeter.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Allison and Roberto Mignone Halls of Gems and Minerals (formerly the **Harry Frank Guggenheim Hall of Gems and Minerals**) is on the first floor, north of the Ross Hall of Meteorites.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It houses thousands of rare gems, minerals specimens and pieces of jewelry.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The halls closed in 2017 to undergo a $32 million redesign by Ralph Appelbaum Associates and reopened to the general public in June 2021.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The redesigned exhibits adopt newer philosophies in exhibit design, including a focus on storytelling, interactivity, and connecting ideas across disciplines.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The halls explore a range of topics, including the diversification of mineral species over the course of Earth's history, plate tectonics, and the stories of specific gems.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The halls display rare samples chosen from among the more than 100,000 pieces in the museum's collection including the Star of India, the Patricia Emerald, and the DeLong Star Ruby.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Gottesman Hall of Planet Earth is on the first floor at the northeast corner of the museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Opened in 1999, it is a permanent hall devoted to the history of Earth, from accretion to the origin of life and contemporary human impacts on the planet.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall was designed to answer five key questions: "How has earth evolved?
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Why are there ocean basins, continents and mountains?
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Why is earth habitable?" The hall features rocks and other objects collected over 28 expeditions; the oldest rock is 4.3 billion years old, while the youngest was collected from a volcano on the day that it solidified.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] There is also a 30-seat granite amphitheater, with a globe, at the center of the hall.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Several sections also discuss the studies of Earth systems, including geology, glaciology, atmospheric sciences, and volcanology.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The exhibit has several large, touchable rock specimens.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall features striking samples of banded iron and deformed conglomerate rocks, as well as granites, sandstones, lavas, and three black smokers.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The north section of the hall, which deals primarily with plate tectonics, is arranged to mimic the Earth's structure, with the core and mantle at the center and crustal features on the perimeter.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Most of the museum's collections of mammalian and dinosaur fossils remain hidden from public view and are kept in many repositories deep within the museum complex.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The most significant storage facility among these is the ten-story Childs Frick Building, which started construction in 1969 and was completed in 1973.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] When the Frick Building was completed, the museum's collection of fossilized mammals and dinosaurs was the world's largest such collection, weighing 600 short tons (540 long tons; 540 t).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Frick Building's top three floors contain laboratories and offices.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Other areas of the museum contain repositories of life from the past.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Whale Bone Storage Room is a cavernous space in which powerful winches come down from the ceiling to move the giant fossil bones about.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The museum attic upstairs includes even more storage facilities, such as the Elephant Room, while the tusk vault and boar vault are downstairs from the attic.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The great fossil collections that are open to public view occupy the entire fourth floor of the museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The fourth floor exhibits are accessed by the Miriam and Ira D.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Wallach Orientation Center, which opened in 1996.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] On the 77th Street side of the museum the visitor begins in the Orientation Center and follows a carefully marked path, which takes the visitor along an evolutionary tree of life.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] As the tree "branches" the visitor is presented with the familial relationships among vertebrates, called cladograms.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] A video projection on the museum's fourth floor introduces visitors to the concept of the cladogram.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Many of the fossils on display represent unique and historic pieces that were collected during the museum's golden era of worldwide expeditions (1880s–1930s).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] On a smaller scale, expeditions continue into the present and have resulted in additions to the collections from Vietnam, Madagascar, South America, and central and eastern Africa.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The first dinosaur hall in the museum opened in 1905.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The dinosaur halls were temporarily closed for renovation starting in 1990.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The first halls to reopen were the primitive-mammal and advanced-mammal halls, part of the Lila Acheson Wallace Wing of Mammals and Their Extinct Relatives, which opened in 1994.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Halls of Saurischian Dinosaurs and Ornithischian Dinosaurs reopened in 1995 as part of a $12 million expansion.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall of Vertebrate Origins opened in 1996.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] A *Triceratops* and a *Stegosaurus* (nicknamed Apex) are also both on display, among many other specimens.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Besides the fossils in museum display, many specimens are stored in the collections available for scientists.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Those include important specimens such as complete diplodocid skull, tyrannosaurid teeth, sauropod vertebrae, and many holotypes.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hayden Planetarium, connected to the museum, is now part of the Rose Center for Earth and Space on the north side of the museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The original Hayden Planetarium was founded in 1933 with a donation by philanthropist Charles Hayden, and it opened in 1935.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The AMNH announced the modern Rose Center for Earth and Space in early 1995, and demolition began the same year.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Frederick Phineas and Sandra Priest Rose Center for Earth and Space was completed in 2000 at a cost of $210 million.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Designed by James Stewart Polshek, the new building consists of a six-story high glass cube enclosing an 87 ft (27 m) illuminated sphere that appears to float, although it is actually supported by truss work.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Polshek has referred to his work as a "cosmic cathedral".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The sphere is known as the Space Theater.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The facility encloses 333,500 sq ft (30,980 m2) of research, education, and exhibition space as well as the Hayden planetarium.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Also in the facility is the Department of Astrophysics, the newest academic research department in the museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Neil DeGrasse Tyson is the director of the Hayden Planetarium.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In addition, Polshek designed the 1,800 sq ft (170 m2) Weston Pavilion, a 43 ft (13 m) high transparent structure of "water white" glass along the museum's west facade.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] This structure, a small companion piece to the Rose Center, offers a new entry way to the museum as well as opening further exhibition space for astronomically related objects.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Heilbrun Cosmic Pathway is one of the most popular exhibits in the Rose Center.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Designed by Studio Gang and landscape architects Reed Hilderbrand, the Richard Gilder Center for Science, Education and Innovation opened in May 2023.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The 230,000-square-foot addition includes six floors above ground, and one below.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Gilder Center welcomes visitors with a new, accessible entrance on Columbus Avenue that connects to central five-story atrium and creates more than 30 connections to the existing museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The atrium's architecture, described as cavern or canyon-like, is informed by natural processes like the movement of wind and water that shape geological landscapes.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] To achieve the continuous visual form, the atrium is constructed with shotcrete.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The curvilinear façade contrasts with the earlier High Victorian Gothic, Richardson Romanesque, and Beaux Arts structures, but its Milford Pink granite cladding is the same stone used on the Museum's west side.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Richard Gilder Center houses new exhibition and display areas devoted to insects, including an insectarium and butterfly vivarium, where visitors can walk among hundreds of live specimens as they flutter about in a lush tropical setting.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It also includes a visible storage structure that houses and displays scientific specimens; an expanded research library; classrooms and education areas, and laboratories.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] This expansion was originally supposed to be north of the existing museum, occupying parts of Theodore Roosevelt Park.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The expansion was relocated to the west side of the existing museum, and its footprint was reduced in size, due to opposition to construction in the park.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The annex replaced three existing buildings along Columbus Avenue's east side.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Founded in 1869, the AMNH Exhibitions Lab has since produced thousands of installations.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The department is notable for its integration of new scientific research into immersive art and multimedia presentations.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In addition to the famous dioramas at its home museum and the Rose Center for Earth and Space, the lab has also produced international exhibitions and software such as the Digital Universe Atlas.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The exhibitions team currently consists of over sixty artists, writers, preparators, designers and programmers.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The department is responsible for the creation of two to three exhibits per year.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] These extensive shows typically travel nationally to sister natural history museums.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] They have produced, among others, the first exhibits to discuss Darwinian evolution, human-induced climate change and the mesozoic mass extinction via asteroid.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Research Library is open to staff and public visitors, and is on the fourth floor of the museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The collection has many retrospective materials, some going back to the 15th century, that are difficult to find elsewhere.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In its early years, the Library expanded its collection mostly through such gifts as John Clarkson Jay's conchological library, Carson Brevoort's library on fishes and general zoology, Daniel Giraud Elliot's ornithological library, S.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Lowell Elliot's collection of books and pamphlets on various subjects, Harry Edwards's entomological library, the Hugh Jewett collection of voyages and travel, and Jules Marcou's geology collection.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In the 1900s, the library continued to grow with donations from figures and organizations such as Egbert Viele, the American Ethnological Society, Joel Asaph Allen, Hermon Carey Bumpus, and Henry Fairfield Osborn.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The new Library was designed by the firm Roche-Dinkeloo in 1992.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The space is 55,000 sq ft (5,100 m2) and includes five different "conservation zones", including the 50-person reading room, public offices, and temperature- and humidity-controlled rooms.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Today, the Library's collections contain over 550,000 volumes of monographs, serials, pamphlets, reprints, microforms, and original illustrations, as well as film, photographic, archives and manuscripts, fine art, memorabilia and rare book collections.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The museum has a scientific staff of more than 225, and sponsors over 120 special field expeditions each year.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Examples of some of these expeditions, financed in whole or part by the AMNH are: Jesup North Pacific Expedition, the Whitney South Seas Expedition, the Roosevelt–Rondon Scientific Expedition, the Crocker Land Expedition, and the expeditions to Madagascar and New Guinea by Richard Archbold.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] On a smaller scale, expeditions continue into the present.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The museum also publishes several peer-reviewed journals, including the *Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History*.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The AMNH operates a biological field station in Portal, Arizona, among the Chiricahua Mountains.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Southwestern Research Station was established in 1955, purchased with a grant from philanthropist David Rockefeller, and with entomologist Mont Cazier as its first director.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The station, in a "biodiversity hotspot", is used by researchers and students, and offers occasional seminars to the public.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] AMNH's education programs include outreach to schools in New York City by the Moveable Museum.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The AMNH offers a wide variety of educational programs, camps, and classes for students from pre-K to post-graduate levels.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The AMNH sponsors the Lang Science Program, a comprehensive 5th–12th grade research and science education program, and the Science Research Mentorship Program (SRMP), in which pairs of students conduct a full year of intensive original research with an AMNH scientist.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] As of 2023, about 400,000 schoolchildren annually take field trips to the AMNH.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Although most students visit for a day or less, since late 2023 the museum has also provided a weeklong educational program called Beyond Elementary Explorations in Science.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] On October 23, 2006, the museum launched the Richard Gilder Graduate School, becoming the first American museum in the United States to award doctoral degrees in its own name.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The school is named for businessman Richard Gilder, who contributed $50 million toward the school.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Accredited in 2009, the school had 11 students enrolled in 2011, who work closely with curators and have access to the collections.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The first seven graduates were awarded their degrees in 2013.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The AMNH offers a Master of Arts in Teaching (MAT) in Earth Science and a PhD in Comparative Biology.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The MAT Earth Science Residency program was launched in 2012 to address a critical shortage of qualified science teachers in New York state.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In 2015, the MAT program officially joined the Richard Gilder Graduate School, with the NYS Board of Regents authorizing the Gilder School to grant the MAT degree.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The museum's first three presidents were all cofounders.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Jesup (1881–1908), bequeathed $1 million to the museum upon his death.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Langdon Jr., (1987–1993) the first president to receive a salary; all previous presidents had served without pay.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The fourth president, Henry Fairfield Osborn, appointed on the death of Jesup, consolidated the museum's expansion and developed it further.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Under Osborn, the museum embraced a growing eugenics movement.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Osborn's friend, noted eugenicist Madison Grant, a member of the museum's executive committee, was the author of the 1916 book, The Passing of the Great Race.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] He also was a funder and shaper of the 1921 Second International Congress of Eugenics, held at the museum**.** Noted eugenicist Charles Davenport presided over the 1932 Third International Eugenics Congress. at the museum as well.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Rice Jr.; and ornithologist Robert Cushman Murphy.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The museum is at 79th Street and Central Park West.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] There is a direct entrance into the museum from the New York City Subway's 81st Street–Museum of Natural History station, served by the B and C trains.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] On a pedestal outside the museum's Columbus Avenue entrance is a stainless steel time capsule, which was created after a design competition that was won by Santiago Calatrava.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The capsule was sealed at the beginning of 2000, to mark the beginning of the 3rd millennium.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It takes the form of a folded saddle-shaped volume, symmetrical on multiple axes, that explores formal properties of folded spherical frames.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The capsule is to be opened in the year 3000.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The museum is in a 17-acre (69,000 m2) city park known as **Theodore Roosevelt Park** that extends from Central Park West to Columbus Avenue, and from West 77th to 81st Streets and that contains park benches, gardens and lawns, and also a dog run.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] On the west side of the park, between 80th and 81st Streets near Columbus Avenue, is the Nobel Monument honoring Nobel Prize winners from the United States.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Having visited the museum, Dabashi reflected on the juxtaposition of scientific progress and what he sees as the persistent legacy of racism in the United States.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The statue of Theodore Roosevelt is seen by Dabashi as a symbol of racial hierarchy and the ongoing struggle to reconcile the nation's past with its present.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The statue would later be removed in 2022, as a consequence of discussions about racism aroused by the 2020 protests surrounding the murder of George Floyd.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] A 2020 article by University of New Hampshire historian Julia Rodriguez contrasts the approaches respectively taken by the AMNH and the Musée de l'Homme in Paris, in terms of their human and cultural exhibits.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] While Rodriguez criticizes the AMNH's exhibits for their failure to acknowledge colonial histories, the Musée de l'Homme has made strides in decolonizing its displays.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Rodriguez also posits that notably absent from such museums are exhibits dedicated to Northern European or New England cultures, suggesting a biased focus on "othering" non-Western societies while normalizing Western cultural norms.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In a June 2024 essay published in Indian online paper ThePrint, Stanford University history professor Priya Satia argues that the museum's Hall of Asian Peoples is problematic because it portrays Asian cultures as static and frozen in time.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Satia believes various misrepresentations can lead to misunderstandings and perpetuate harmful biases against Asian and Middle Eastern people.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In the same essay, Satia also delves into parts of the museum's own history, such as its 1921 hosting of the Second International Eugenics Congress.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Her essay was criticized by Samuel Abrams, who serves as a Nonresident Senior Fellow of the American Enterprise Institute, as a researcher at NYU, and as a Professor of Politics at Sarah Lawrence College.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/api] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The **Biodiversity Heritage Library** (**BHL**) is the world’s largest open-access digital library for biodiversity literature and archives.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The BHL consortium works with the international taxonomic community, publishers, bioinformaticians, and information technology professionals to develop tools and services to facilitate greater access, interoperability, and reuse of content and data.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] BHL provides a range of services, data exports, and APIs to allow users to download content, harvest source data files, and reuse materials for research purposes.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] Through taxonomic intelligence tools developed by Global Names Architecture, BHL indexes the taxonomic names throughout the collection, allowing researchers to locate publications about specific taxa.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] In partnership with the Internet Archive and through local digitization efforts, BHL's portal provides free access to hundreds of thousands of volumes, comprising over 59 million pages, from the 15th–21st centuries.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] Founded in 2006, BHL soon became the third broad digitization project for biodiversity literature, after Gallica and AnimalBase.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] In 2008, the size of Gallica and AnimalBase was passed, and BHL is now by far the world's largest digitization project for biodiversity literature.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] It was the literature cornerstone of the *Encyclopedia of Life*.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] Initially, the Biodiversity Heritage Library was a collaboration of ten natural history and botanical libraries and currently it has fourteen members.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] Since 2009, the BHL has expanded globally.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The European Commission's eContentPlus program has funded the as Biodiversity Heritage Library for Europe.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The BHL Europe project consisted of 28 consortium partners, mostly European libraries.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The project closed in 2012, but many participating institutions remain active as BHL partners.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] Shortly thereafter another project BHL-China was launched in Beijing, in collaboration with the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] Since then BHL in the strict sense has been called BHL-US/UK (usually only BHL-US), the global project has been referred to as BHL-Global, to distinguish it from the US/UK project.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The global BHL project is managed primarily by the Smithsonian Institution (Washington, D.C.), Natural History Museum (London), and Missouri Botanical Garden.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] In 2010, the Atlas of Living Australia created a regional node for Australia.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The digitisation operation is hosted by Museums Victoria and is nationally funded by the ALA.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] Australia's museums, herbaria, royal societies, field naturalist clubs and government organisations make up the contributors.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] Additionally, Brazil (through SciELO), and the Bibliotheca Alexandrina have also created regional BHL nodes.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] These projects will work together to share content, protocols, services, and digital preservation practices.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] There is an online BHL portal featuring Google Maps API integration, AJAX, tag clouds, and JPEG2000 images that facilitate multi-resolution zoom and pan.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The Biodiversity Heritage Library is managed by a Secretariat headquartered at Smithsonian Libraries and Archives in Washington, DC.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] An Executive Committee, elected by Biodiversity Heritage Library Members, provides strategic direction.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The Secretariat is led by the BHL Program Director.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] Thomas Garnett served in that position (2006–2012) and was succeeded by Martin R.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] Kelli Trei (Biosciences Librarian and Associate Professor from the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign) was appointed Transition Director in May 2025.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The Biodiversity Heritage Library was awarded the 2010 John Thackray Medal of the Society for the History of Natural History.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] This award "recognizes significant achievements in the history or bibliography of natural history".
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] In March 2012, the Missouri Botanical Garden received $260,000 in funding from the National Endowment for the Humanities to identify and describe natural history illustrations from the digitized books and journals in the online Biodiversity Heritage Library.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The Art of Life project will develop software tools for automated identification and description of visual resources contained within the more than 100,000 volumes and 38 million pages of core historic literature made available through BHL digitization activities.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] IDG's Computerworld Honors Program announced on March 19, 2013 the Biodiversity Heritage Library as a 2013 laureate.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The annual award program honors visionary applications of information technology promoting positive social, economic, and educational change.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] In May 2013, the Biodiversity Heritage Library was the recipient of the Charles Robert Long Award of Extraordinary Merit from the Council on Botanical and Horticultural Libraries.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The award is the highest honor bestowed by the council, honoring outstanding contributions and meritorious service to the field of botanical and horticultural literature, with only 14 recipients named since 1988.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] In October 2015, the Biodiversity Heritage Library was awarded the Internet Archive’s Internet Heroes at the 2015 Library Leaders’ Forum in San Francisco, 21–23 October 2015.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The Digital Library Federation named the Biodiversity Heritage Library a joint winner (along with the American Archive of Public Broadcasting) of the DLF 2016 Community/Capacity Award.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The award recognizes collection action over individual achievement and honors community-minded capacity building in digital libraries, archives and museums.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] In appreciation of the services to taxonomists, a species of snail from Laos was named *Vargapupa biheli* in 2015, the species name derived from the initials BHL.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] A second species, a new species of fossil robber fly, *Kishenehnoasilus bhl* was named after the Biodiversity Heritage Library in 2019.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The primary funding for the Biodiversity Heritage Library came via the Encyclopedia of Life through a grant from the John D. and Catherine T.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] Additional grants have been received from The Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation, The Richard Lounsbery Foundation, the Institute of Museum and Library Services (IMLS).
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] The Council on Library and Information Resources (CLIR) awarded the Biodiversity Heritage Library funding in 2015 as part of the Digitizing Hidden Special Collections and Archives program $491,713 to support increased accessibility to original scientific documentation found in archival field notes.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] Members of the Biodiversity Heritage Library also have received generous support from their parent institutions.
[src:biodiversity-heritage-library/biodiversity-heritage-library] In addition to staffing and other costs, direct contributions have included the Atherton Seidell Endowment Fund by the Smithsonian Institution.
